    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-03-11T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-03-11T18:00:00-05:00" n="400"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d400">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">812.00Sonora/236: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul at Chihuahua</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Myers</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-11T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >March 11, 1929—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Your March 8, 6 p.m.<note n="11" xml:id="d400fn11">See telegram of March 9, 11
                        a.m., from the Consul at Nogales, <ref target="#pg_354">p. 354</ref>.</note>
                    is not clear to the Department. What do you mean by General Moseley’s “warning”
                    to the Governor of Chihuahua and on whom did it make “a very bad
                    impression”?</p>
                <p>See Department’s circular of March 8, 8 p.m.<note n="12" xml:id="d400fn12">See
                        telegram No. 81, March 8, midnight, to the Ambassador in Mexico, <ref
                            target="#pg_354">p. 354</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kellogg</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
